  "articleSummary": "This tutorial argues that formatting numbers and currency correctly is essential for internationalized applications, as numbers are locale-specific (e.g., decimal separators, grouping) while currency values are global but must be displayed according to the user’s locale. Key points include the distinction between localization (L10n) and internationalization (i18n), the use of ISO standards (ISO 3166 for locales, ISO 4217 for currency codes), and a client-side solution using JavaScript’s `Intl.NumberFormat`. The tone is conversational and instructive, with humor and emoji metaphors (“Numbers are Local 🏘️, Currency is Global 🌎”). The intended audience is developers building ecommerce or payment systems who need to avoid the “dead give-away” of incorrectly formatted prices.",
